dict.string: Search and add bookmarks to Raindrop.io
tell application id "com.runningwithcrayons.Alfred" to run trigger "browse" in workflow "me.westerlind.alfred.raindrop-search"
tell application id "com.runningwithcrayons.Alfred" to run trigger "search" in workflow "me.westerlind.alfred.raindrop-search"

property ff_dir: (system attribute "alfred_workflow_cache") property ff_path: ff_dir & "/firefox_current_tab.json" property ff_file: POSIX file ff_path
on run
tell application "System Events" set frontApp to name of first application process whose frontmost is true end tell
set browserURL to "No browser active" set browserTitle to ""
if (frontApp = "Safari") then tell application "Safari" set browserURL to the URL of the current tab of the front window set browserTitle to the name of the current tab of the front window end tell else if (frontApp = "Microsoft Edge") then set browserURL to do shell script "/usr/bin/osascript browser-info/edge-url.scpt" set browserTitle to do shell script "/usr/bin/osascript browser-info/edge-title.scpt" else if (frontApp = "Google Chrome") then set browserURL to do shell script "/usr/bin/osascript browser-info/chrome-url.scpt" set browserTitle to do shell script "/usr/bin/osascript browser-info/chrome-title.scpt" else if (frontApp = "Google Chrome Canary") then set browserURL to do shell script "/usr/bin/osascript browser-info/chrome-canary-url.scpt" set browserTitle to do shell script "/usr/bin/osascript browser-info/chrome-canary-title.scpt" else if (frontApp = "Chromium") then set browserURL to do shell script "/usr/bin/osascript browser-info/chromium-url.scpt" set browserTitle to do shell script "/usr/bin/osascript browser-info/chromium-title.scpt" else if (frontApp = "Brave Browser") then set browserURL to do shell script "/usr/bin/osascript browser-info/brave-url.scpt" set browserTitle to do shell script "/usr/bin/osascript browser-info/brave-title.scpt" else if (frontApp = "Whale") then set browserURL to do shell script "/usr/bin/osascript browser-info/whale-url.scpt" set browserTitle to do shell script "/usr/bin/osascript browser-info/whale-title.scpt" else if (frontApp = "Safari Technology Preview") then set browserURL to do shell script "/usr/bin/osascript browser-info/safari-techpreview-url.scpt" set browserTitle to do shell script "/usr/bin/osascript browser-info/safari-techpreview-title.scpt" else if (frontApp = "Opera") then set browserURL to do shell script "/usr/bin/osascript browser-info/opera-url.scpt" set browserTitle to do shell script "/usr/bin/osascript browser-info/opera-title.scpt" else if (frontApp = "Vivaldi") then set browserURL to do shell script "/usr/bin/osascript browser-info/vivaldi-url.scpt" set browserTitle to do shell script "/usr/bin/osascript browser-info/vivaldi-title.scpt" else if (frontApp = "firefox") then -- For getting tab info from Firefox, we use the awsome Firefox Assistant by Dean Jackson, because Firefox does not have Apple Script support like the other browsers. -- Ensure directory exists do shell script "mkdir -p " & quoted form of ff_dir -- Ensure JSON file does not do shell script "rm -f " & quoted form of ff_path
-- Tell Firefox Assistant to write tab info to ff_path try tell application id "com.runningwithcrayons.Alfred" run trigger "current-tab" in workflow "net.deanishe.alfred.firefox-assistant" with argument ff_path end tell on error errMsg log "ERROR: " & quoted form of errMsg return do shell script "/usr/bin/php firefox-error-management.php " & quoted form of errMsg end try
-- External Trigger calls are asynchronous, so wait up to one second for file to appear, -- then return contents of file (which are written to STDOUT) tell application "Finder" repeat 100 times try if exists ff_file then set ff_tab_info to do shell script "cat " & quoted form of ff_path -- Remove JSON file do shell script "rm -f " & quoted form of ff_path if (ff_tab_info is equal to "Cannot Connect to Extension") then return do shell script "/usr/bin/php firefox-error-management.php " & quoted form of ff_tab_info else return do shell script "/usr/bin/php raindrop-collections.php " & quoted form of ff_tab_info & " \"{query}\"" end if end if on error errMsg log "ERROR: " & quoted form of errMsg return do shell script "/usr/bin/php firefox-error-management.php " & quoted form of errMsg end try delay 0.01 end repeat end tell
-- Failed to get tab info (in time) log "Tab info not saved by Firefox Assistant" return do shell script "/usr/bin/php firefox-error-management.php \"Tab info not saved by Firefox Assistant\"" end if
do shell script "/usr/bin/php raindrop-collections.php " & quoted form of browserURL & " \"{query}\" " & quoted form of browserTitle & " " & quoted form of (system attribute "subcollections_as_full_paths")
end run
tell application "System Events" set frontApp to name of first application process whose frontmost is true end tell return frontApp
tell application id "com.runningwithcrayons.Alfred" to run trigger "set_tags" in workflow "me.westerlind.alfred.raindrop-search" with argument "{query}"

SETTINGS Change the Workflow Environment Variables to adjust the settings
subcollections_as_full_paths: Set this to true if you prefer that subcollections are always rendered as full paths (like "collection/subcollection"), instead of like a tree view which is the default. You see this (if you have subcollections) in the collection listing while selecting to browse collections, or while selecting a collection for a new bookmark.
description_in_boomark_listing: When listing bookmarks while searching for or browsing them, by default you will get info about the collection, tags, and domain name in the subtitle of each bookmark, and you can hold down the ctrl key to view the description. If you set this to true, you will instead see the description first and can hold the ctrl key to view collection, tags and domain name.
ABOUT THIS WORKFLOW This Alfred workflow is created to have a single, fast, and always reachable way of searching Raindrop.io, and then open bookmarks in the web browser you are currently working in, even if that's not your default browser. You can also use this workflow to add bookmarks to Raindrop.io from the browser you are currently using.
- To search your Raindrop.io bookmarks, open Alfred, type r, space, and then your search query, and the results will show directly in Alfred so that you can select one and press enter to open it in your browser. - Raindrop.io collections and tags will also show in the search results together with bookmarks, and you can select them to browse or search their content. - Before you have started to type a search query, you also have the option to browse your collections instead of starting with a search. - If a web browser is the frontmost app when you open a bookmark from this workflow, it will open in that browser. - If you are working in another app, the bookmark will open in your default browser. - Hold the cmd-key to view the URL for a bookmark. - Hold the ctrl-key to view the description for a bookmark. - Hold the option-key while pressing enter, or use cmd+c to copy the URL instead of opening it in a browser. - Press enter before you have started typing a search query, and Raindrop.io itself will open in your active web browser. - To add a new bookmark to Raindrop.io, first make sure that you have the webpage you want to add opened in a browser and that it is the frontmost window, and then open Alfred and type ra followed by a space - In the first step you choose collection for the new bookmark, and you can either type to search for the collection you want to add the new bookmark to or just select one in the list. Hold the cmd-key to save when you select the collection, and skip setting a custom title or adding tags. - In the second step you get to change the title that the bookmark is saved with. Hold the cmd-key to save and skip the tag adding step. - In the third step you get to add tags to your new bookmark. You can either simply type them out, or select from a list of tags that matches what you have started to type. Separate multiple tags with comma. Hold the cmd-key to save when selecting a tag in the list, and skip the option of adding more tags. - The Firefox support for adding bookmarks was made possible with the help of deanishe's great workflow Firefox Assistant, which needs to be installed in Alfred for the Firefox support to function. Get it here: https://github.com/deanishe/alfred-firefox - If the workflow is not authenticated with Raindrop.io when you initiate it, you will be taken to the authentication process.
Add tags to the new bookmark
If a browser is the frontmost app, open the webpage in that browser, or otherwise open it in the default browser.
Set title for the new bookmark
